tspan.tspan: As we embark on this second issue of InScight, we're
reminded of the power of curiosity and the thrill of
discovery. We're delighted to present a diverse range of
articles and interviews that showcase the wonders of

text.tspan: science.

tspan.tspan: Building on the feedback from our inaugural issue, we've
endeavored to improve and expand our coverage to bring
you the most exciting and relevant stories in science. This
issue features in-depth articles on cutting-edge space
research, exploring the latest developments and
innovations in the field. Our biotech section delves into the
latest breakthroughs and advancements, highlighting their
potential impact on our lives. We're also examining the
complex and pressing issues surrounding climate science,
and exploring the rapidly evolving world of artificial
intelligence (AI). Additionally, we're thrilled to include
interviews with distinguished experts, such as Prof. Probal
Chaudhuri from Indian Statistical Institute and Dr. Srijita Ray
our very own BS-MS alumni from the Department of Earth
Sciences, who share their insights and experiences in their

text.tspan: respective fields.

tspan.tspan: A notable highlight is Prof. Neelanjana Sengupta's
(Department of Biological Sciences) thought-provoking
article exploring the potential of AI in achieving the Nobel
Prize in 2024. We're proud to share these stories and
insights with you, and we hope you'll enjoy this issue as

text.tspan: much as we did putting it together.

tspan.tspan: We extend our gratitude to our contributors, reviewers, and
editorial team for their tireless efforts. We're committed to
making InScight a vibrant platform for science discussion,

text.tspan: where everyone can engage, explore, and learn.

tspan.tspan: So grab a cup of coffee, sit back, and dive in! We'd love to
hear your thoughts, feedback, and ideas. Join us on this

text.tspan: journey of exploration and discovery.
Let's ignite a passion for science, together!

INSCIGHT
Prof. Ayan Banerjee,
Department of Physical Sciences,
IISER Kolkata
#page#

text.style: font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;font-stretch:normal;font-size:13.3333px;line-height:1;font-family:'Cooper Hewitt LO';-inkscape-font-specification:'Cooper Hewitt LO, Normal';font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-variant-numeric:normal;font-variant-east-asian:normal;text-align:justify;text-decoration-color:#000000;writing-mode:lr-tb;direction:ltr;white-space:pre-wrap;shape-inside:url(#rect4-4-02-2-5-9-2-3-6) url(#rect4-4-02-2-5-9-2-3-6-5);display:inline;fill:#202020;fill-opacity:1;stroke:none;stroke-width:7.55906;paint-order:markers stroke fill

tspan.tspan: Science is a method. Science is a habit. Science is an
attitude. That defines a human being. It is not a mere

text.tspan: profession that you practice between nine to five.

tspan.tspan: But these weren't the reasons for which I studied science. I
took Physics after school because I didn't want to be an
engineer, and I had a mentor during my twelfth standard who
was passionately in love with the subject. Even then, I had
actually applied for honours in Economics at one of Kolkata’s
top colleges since my family were not really ready to let me
pursue Physics after I had steadfastly refused to get into
Engineering. It was only because I was waitlisted in that
college in the first round of admissions (with a verbal
assurance that I could get my chance in the second round in
a month) that I took up Physics at another college. After
arguing that there wasn't really a ‘written’ guarantee that I
would get the call-up from the top college, was there (that
was the latent administrator in me speaking, actually, and

text.tspan: somehow my family couldn't argue me out)?!

tspan.tspan: And then, somehow Physics grew in me. Slowly, steadily. In
our times, college and even University education was
entirely based on exams, and especially the Bachelor's
exams were really an ordeal. Four hours of gut-wrenching
regurgitation, with six sixteen mark questions to crack in the
theory papers. Somehow I managed to sail my ship without
sinking for those five years, and landed up at the shores of

text.tspan: IISc.

tspan.tspan: Those eight years at IISc essentially made a physicist out of
me. That too, for the first four years I struggled endlessly,
for I was into experiments, and in a lab with an advisor who
joined the institute only six months before me, and loved to
take apart a cycle (and expected me to do so too - me who
had led an utterly protected life in crowded South Kolkata
with no need ever to even touch a cycle). I was caught short
at almost everything, and often wanted to run away, but
somehow didn't, because somewhere deep down, I knew

text.tspan: that I had nothing else to do.

tspan.tspan: And now, I often think that it was the wonder I have always
felt looking at the night sky which ensured that I would stick
to the path which revealed secrets about nature. That
ensured that almost every day I lived I learnt something new,
which - most interestingly, perhaps very few people in the
world were aware of. Since you can only publish papers if

text.tspan: reviewers agree that the work hasn't been done before.

tspan.tspan: Noone told me these things when I was young. Absolutely
noone. We didn't have institutes like the IISERs those days,
where you could study science after you left school and
found cutting edge research happening around you. Where
you could enter an utterly dark room with red blue green
laser beams cutting the darkness like Light Swords in
Fantasy movies to trigger the romantic in you when you were
eighteen. Where you learnt that light and electricity and
chemicals and cells could tell you stories more magnificent
than the human imagination can conjure. With every inch of
them consistent and logical and often written in the most

text.tspan: truthful language of all, Mathematics.

tspan.tspan: My colleges didn't have science magazines. Even IISc didn't
have one when we were around. That IISER Kolkata has had
‘Cogito’ first, and now ‘Inscight’, makes me happy to belong
to this place. We are living in difficult times now, with a world
seemingly hell-bent on defying and denying the scientific
method, and preferring dogma above diagnosis. Even our
survival on this planet after a century may not be so
straightforward. Only young minds with the ability to
comprehend and communicate using the insights and
intuition provided by adapting the methods of science can

text.tspan: dig us out of this ever deepening hole.
Live your science, don't just practice it!
